{"id":"astro-ph/0210165","submitter":"Lloyd Knox","authors":"M. Kamionkowski (Caltech) and Lloyd Knox (UC Davis)","title":"Aspects of the Cosmic Microwave Background Dipole","comments":"dedicated to the memory of David Wilkinson submitted to PRD","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. D67 (2003) 063001","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.67.063001","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Cosmic microwave background (CMB) experiments generally infer a temperature\nfluctuation from a measured intensity fluctuation through the first term in the\nTaylor expansion of the Planck function, the relation between the intensity in\na given frequency and the temperature. However, with the forthcoming Planck\nsatellite, and perhaps even with the Microwave Anisotropy Probe, the CMB-dipole\namplitude will be large enough to warrant inclusion of the next higher order\nterm. To quadratic order in the dipole amplitude, there is an intensity\nquadrupole induced by the dipole with a frequency dependence given by the\nsecond derivative of the Planck function. The Planck satellite should be able\nto detect this dipole-induced intensity quadrupole and distinguish it through\nits frequency depdendence from the intrinsic CMB temperature and foreground\nquadrupoles. This higher-order effect provides a robust pre-determined target\nthat may provide tests of Planck's and MAP's large-angle-fluctuation\nmeasurements and of their techniques for multi-frequency foreground\nsubtraction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Oct 2002 21:27:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
